Mechanical feedback between membrane tension and dynamics
Nils C. Gauthier1, Thomas A. Masters1 and Michael P. Sheetz1,2
1 Mechanobiology Institute, National University of Singapore, 5A Engineering Drive 1, Singapore 117411 2 Department of Biological Sciences, Columbia University, New York, NY 10027, USA
The plasma membrane represents a physical inelastic barrier with a given area that adheres to the underlying cytoskeleton. The tension in the membrane physically affects cell functions and recent studies have highlighted that this physical signal orchestrates complex aspects of trafficking and motility. Despite its undeniable importance, little is known about the mechanisms by which membrane tension regulates cell functions or stimulates signals. The maintenance of membrane tension is also a matter of debate, particularly the nature of the membrane reservoir and trafficking pathways that buffer tension. In this review we discuss the importance of membrane area and of tension as a master integrator of cell functions, particularly for membrane traffic.
Membrane tension and area
In the past, we have discussed the role that tension in the plasma membrane of animal cells plays in the mechanical functions of cell motility, endocytosis, and membrane resealing [1–3]. It appears that tension acts as a break on the rate of those functions and coordinates them at the whole-cell level. Because of the large surface area to volume ratio of most mammalian cells, the tension seems to be primarily set by the adhesion between the membrane and the cytoskeleton. A recent review [4] highlighted the integrating role of the plasma membrane in cell motility, particularly focusing on the dynamic interplay and the feedback between the biochemical and biophysical characteristics of the membrane. Recent studies have also highlighted the importance of tension in controlling complex transitions in cell motility [5], polarization [6], shape maintenance [7], and overall membrane area [5,8]. Although the concept of membrane tension (see Glossary) has been extensively explained previously [1–3], it is important to remember some basic principles (Box 1). Membrane tension is defined by two main components. The first is the in-plane tension in the lipid bilayer, mainly due to hydrostatic pressure. The second is membrane–cytoskeleton adhesion, mediated by phospholipidbinding proteins, which can be linked downstream to actin cytoskeleton remodeling through polymerization or contraction. However, the relative magnitude of each contribution depends on cell state and remains unclear, because they are interdependent; for example, actin polymerization
pushing the membrane outward will clearly increase the in-plane term [5,6]. Experimentally, membrane tension is determined from the force required to maintain a small membrane tube, or tether, extracted from the cell plasma membrane. Usually, tethers are pulled with an optically trapped bead [9]. The force extracted from the bead displacement from equilibrium depends on both in-plane tension and cytoskeleton adhesion components. As opposed to pure lipid vesicles devoid of cytoskeleton, in most mammalian cells the positive intracellular pressure is balanced by the strength of the adhesion between the membrane and the cytoskeleton. The typical tensions that have been measured (proportional to the square of the force required to pull the tether) range from 0.01 to 0.04 mN/m. When membrane–cytoskeleton adhesion is reduced – for example, by the loss of PI(4,5)P2, actin depolymerization, ERM protein depletion, or the loss of myosin 1B – the membrane balloons out in a bleb. In blebbing regions the tension that arises purely from hydrostatic pressure is typically fourfold lower [10]. Thus, the adhesion between the membrane and the cytoskeleton is a major determinant of membrane tension and is what causes the membrane to conform to the surface of the cytoskeleton. The range of membrane tensions observed for mammalian cells is much lower than the forces needed to open bacterial stretch channels (2–10 mN/m) or lyse membrane (10 mN/m). This indicates that mammalian cells must employ sensitive membrane remodeling mechanisms to buffer tension changes that operate in this smaller range. For instance, mammal-specific stretch-activated channels have been described but still seem to operate at a higher tension threshold [11].
