the same molecular components remains a mystery. One possible explanation may be linked to the membrane tension continuum (same membrane tension in the entire cell surface) and to the adhesive nature of the protruding structure, whereas folds do not adhere to the substrate. Because the lamellipodium (protruding region) is attached to the substrate, actin polymerization will push the membrane forward but this actin, in turn, will have to sustain some resistance from the membrane (membrane tension). This resistance may be transmitted through the actin network toward adhesions at the back of the lamellipodium that will in turn provide anchorage to the substrate to move forward [16]. By contrast, the cytoskeleton supporting the membrane in the folds or ruffles is not attached directly to the substrate and will have an older, less dense actin network that can be absorbed inside the cell. As a consequence, folds will disappear rapidly, providing substantial amounts of extra membrane area because those structures have a high surface to volume ratio.
Membrane wrinkles or ‘micro-folds’
By pulling membrane tethers from already adherent fibroblasts at constant force, a rather small (0.3–1% of the total membrane area) membrane buffer was identified [17]. This buffer compensates for small changes in tension and its capacity is linked to actin cytoskeleton integrity [17]. However, the physical nature of the buffer was not identified. Given the very small size of this reservoir, it appears to be different than that used for spreading. Several possible mechanisms can be imagined: some wrinkles or microfolds (Figure 1) could be present at the cell surface due to local proteolipidic heterogeneity or there may be small
membrane invaginations such as caveolae or active endocytic–exocytic processes.
Caveolae
Recently, caveolae have been proposed as a major tension buffer [14,18]. Caveolae are small (60–80 nm in diameter) plasma membrane invaginations [19] that depend on cholesterol and sphingolipids as well as caveolin proteins [19] (Figure 1e). Knockout of caveolin 1 results in caveolar disassembly and has been used to address the function of these structures [20,21]. On osmotic swelling to increase membrane tension, disassembly of caveolae was observed [14], as previously reported for mechanical stress [22,23]. Moreover, caveolin 1-depleted cells (devoid of caveolae) were unable to buffer membrane tension [14]. In this case, the membrane tension increased by almost threefold for several minutes, whereas control caveolin 1-positive cells restored a normal level of tension under the same experimental conditions [14]. This implied that caveolin 1 (and so probably caveolae) was required to absorb tension shocks. Surprisingly, osmotic swelling does not seem to affect cytoskeletal organization, although the cell volume increases by 35% [14]. The estimated area in caveolae is only 0.3% of the membrane area [14], which resembles the buffer size in tether extensions from spread cells [17]. By contrast, a much larger membrane buffer (>10% of membrane area in the form of folds) was estimated to buffer the membrane area during spreading [5]. Caveolae are endocytosed on detachment of spread cells and return to the plasma membrane during spreading [24,25]. In the light of these results, it appears that cells can use different types of buffer. Chronologically, it seems that the primary buffer of
