Vacuole-like dilations and blebs
Blebs (Figure 1c) and vacuole-like dilations (VLDs) (Figure 1d) are two other major membrane formations that participate in membrane tension maintenance and could be considered as mirror images of each other. Blebs are spherical membrane evaginations devoid of actin cytoskeleton (at least at early times [26]) that form in response to outward pressure; VLDs are spherical membrane invaginations that appear in the ventral surface of cells in response to inward pressure [12]. Blebs appear when the membrane–cytoskeleton attachment is too weak to sustain the fluid pressure created by inward contraction of the actin cytoskeleton. This can be due to an increase in the overall contractile tension or to weakening of the membrane–cytoskeleton attachment. The spherical nature of the bleb gives it a minimal surface area to volume ratio and represents an excellent mechanism for the cell to efficiently relax membrane and cortical tension (Box 1) [27]. Blebs rarely appear in resting cells subjected to osmotic swelling, indicating that the primary reason for their formation is weakening of membrane–cytoskeleton attachment. When cells are dying or ill, they often form huge blebs that do not heal, whereas active cells rapidly heal blebs by the assembly of an actin cytoskeleton. The low tether force of early blebs increases rapidly on the assembly of actin filaments on the bleb membrane [10]. By contrast, VLDs are structures well described in shrinking neurons, but are also clearly visible in fibroblasts during osmotic or mechanically induced shrinkage [12]. VLDs form in a matter of seconds from the ventral surface of the cell and penetrate into the cytoplasm. VLD formation is the direct consequence of the shrinkage of swollen cells that have an excess of membrane area that needs to be resorbed. Because the membrane tension drops only slightly below normal when VLDs form, the affinity of the membrane for the cytoskeleton is maintained during shrinking [28]. VLDs shrink rapidly, presumably by the formation of endocytic vesicles or possibly endocytic tubules. The ventral location of VLDs can be explained by a weakened actin cytoskeleton between adhesion sites. Both outward and inward pockets of membrane can form in response to outward or inward pressures, but outward bleb formation in active cells involves the inward contraction of the cytoskeleton by myosin; hence, the inhibitor of myosin is named blebbistatin because it blocks bleb formation [29].
Ongoing endocytic and exocytic processes
In addition to the readily available plasma membrane buffer, the cell can also modulate membrane area in response to variations of membrane tension using endomembranes by exo- and endocytosis (discussed below). As the
membrane invaginations formed by these processes are part of the plasma membrane continuum they are sensitive to membrane tension changes (Figure 1f). For example, endocytosis has been described to be strongly hyperactivated after a rapid drop in tension [30].
Crosstalk between membrane trafficking and membrane tension
Increases in membrane tension have been described to activate exocytosis and inhibit endocytosis [31]. Conversely, a decrease in tension slows exocytosis and increases endocytosis [31]. These opposite effects will produce opposite changes in plasma membrane area and indicate that a major response to changes in membrane tension involves changes in membrane trafficking. However, the control of endomembrane trafficking by membrane tension is more difficult to tackle experimentally and is poorly understood.
Endocytosis
In the case of endocytosis (Figure 3), it is easy to understand that vesicle formation will involve active inward bending of the membrane that is resisted by membrane tension resulting in an inverse relation between membrane tension and endocytosis rate [1,13,28,31]. Recently, an elegant study shed some light on this process [32]. It was previously assumed that the clathrin-mediated endocytic pathway was independent of the actin cytoskeleton. Progress in live cell microscopy and refinement in observations has shown that in fact an actin machinery, at least in some cell types (particularly in yeast [33]), is involved in clathrin-mediated endocytosis [34]. The new study proves that variations in membrane tension were linked to the actin machinery [32]. When tension was high, the authors observed that the actin machinery was recruited and served as the main driving force needed to promote vesicle budding. However, when tension was low, the actin machinery was disposable and vesicles could form easily. Clathrin-mediated endocytosis was not the only pathway sensitive to membrane tension; clathrin-independent endocytic pathways also appeared to be linked to membrane area and tension regulation (discussed below).
Exocytosis
During cell spreading, an increase in membrane tension activates net exocytosis equivalent to half of the suspended-cell membrane area [5,8] (Figure 2c). The vesicles originate from a rapidly recycling membrane pool – containing Glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI)-anchored proteins – that is microtubule independent [8]. How can an increase in membrane tension activate exocytosis? One simple hypothesis can be drawn from previous observations in plants and membrane fusion models [12,35–37]. Vesicles could be pre-docked and the increase in membrane tension overcomes the fusion energy barrier. This could explain the tension-mediated but calcium-independent membrane fusion reported for plasma membrane area regulation in plants [12]. Modeling studies also indicate that an optimal membrane tension is required for proper vesicle fusion [35]. Using a cell mimicry assay, a similar situation was reported where vesicle fusion occurs as membrane tension increases [36]. However, in these two
