The CLIC/GEEC pathways (Figure 3) were identified when ligands such as bacterial toxins continued to enter mammalian cells after clathrin-mediated endocytosis was blocked. For example Aeromonas hydrophila Aerolysin toxin and the Helicobacter pylori VacA cytotoxin have been reported to hijack the GPI-anchored protein endocytic pathway. Some toxins, such as the Shiga toxin [44], were also able to induce endocytosis through an endocytic pathway that shared several morphological characteristics with the CLIC/GEEC pathways [45]. Several studies have indicated that these endocytic recycling pathways were the main contributors to membrane area regulation, making them excellent candidates to respond to and regulate membrane tension [8,41,42]. They involved tubulovesicular structures up to several micrometers in length, indicating that they harbored a large amount of membrane area sufficient for tension adjustment [5]. Moreover, by measuring the surface area to volume ratio, the CLIC pathway was estimated to be able to turn over the entire plasma membrane of a fibroblast in less than 12 min [41,42] – fast enough to account for the recycling capacity of the GPI-anchored protein pathway reported to increase membrane area during fibroblast spreading [8].
Link to the actin cytoskeleton and Rho GTPases
Most studies report that clathrin-independent endocytosis is highly dependent on the integrity of the actin cytoskeleton. The actin cytoskeleton is also a major contributor to cell shape maintenance and cell migration. Surprisingly, the Rho GTPases – Rho, Rac, and Cdc42 –contribute both to cell migration and to endocytosis of CLICs/GEECs [4648] (Figure 3). Rho promotes formation of stress fibers and is linked to interleukin 2 receptor (IL-2R) endocytosis [47]. Cdc42 promotes filopodium formation and VacA toxin and GPI-anchored protein endocytosis [46,48]. Finally, Rac promotes lamellipodium formation, macropinocytosis, and phagocytosis. These are endocytic pathways that share some similarities with the CLICs/GEECs [40]. Reevaluating these studies in light of today’s knowledge, it appears clear that by modifying these GTPases, cell shape maintenance and cell migration functions will be perturbed. As a consequence, the endocytic machinery mainly implicated in this process is the CLIC/GEEC pathway, and it will be affected because membrane area and tension will require readjustment. Several recent studies have put membrane area and tension at the center stage of cell migration and shape maintenance [4–7,16,49,50], and a more global picture can now be drawn linking the CLIC/GEEC endocytic recycling pathways with cell migration because of membrane area and tension maintenance.
Membrane tension orchestrates cell migration First experimental evidence
More than a decade ago, lamellipodium protrusion was shown to be inversely related to membrane tension [51]. At about the same time, separate findings suggested that membrane trafficking was directly linked to both membrane tension regulation and cell shape changes, particularly in mitosis [13]. However, with the exception of mitosis [17], these effects were primarily linked to externally or internally induced mechanical or chemical modifications.
Results from modeling
Several modeling studies supported the idea that membrane tension controls the rate of motility, because the postulation of an inverse correlation between tension and motility rate best explains the observed motility [7,16,50,52,53]. Protrusive events were proposed to be limited by membrane tension [16]. Using keratocytes as a model system, migration was modeled by taking into account actin polymerization and treadmilling inside an inextensible bag of membrane, with membrane tension as a mechanical feedback to control shape changes [4,7,52]. However, unlike fibroblasts, keratocytes do not form focal adhesions and remodel their membrane area with endomembrane at a relatively lower rate. Moreover, in none of the studies above was the membrane tension measured experimentally, nor the membrane area regulation properly addressed.
New experimental findings
Recent findings in the fibroblast system provided the first example that cells employ membrane tension as a global master regulator of overall shape by ‘sensing’ tension changes and adjusting the actomyosin cytoskeleton and membrane trafficking accordingly [5,6,49,54] (Figure 2). These observations have been extended to neutrophils, in which a membrane tension increase is observed during lamellipodial protrusion [6]. Moreover, the increase in membrane tension after polarization was postulated to reinforce polarity by restricting lamellipodial protrusions to one side of the cell and retraction to the other side of the cell (Figure 2f). Membrane tension appears to be a major contributor to cell polarity acquisition and maintenance. This point is further supported by observations in Caenorhabditis elegans sperm cells [55]. Nematodes lack actin, their cytoskeletons instead comprising major sperm protein (MSP). By lowering membrane tension during nematode sperm cell motion, the organization of the MSP cytoskeleton was perturbed, affecting the cell leading edge organization and slowing cell motion, whereas increasing membrane tension enhanced motility. An optimal level of tension is thus required to maintain MSP cytoskeletal organization and motility [55], underlining a possible influence of membrane tension on the actin cytoskeletal organization in mammalian systems as suggested by modeling studies. This brings us to the final part of this review and to the major questions that now emerge.
Concluding remarks
To play its role as a global regulator, the physical signal of tension needs to be transmitted to the well-established biochemical responses known to regulate functions such as trafficking and migration. During these processes, the physical aspect of the signal could also induce more biomechanical consequences, such as protein stretching and extension that could lead to biochemical signaling. Recent reviews and commentaries have already proposed some interesting hypotheses and future areas of interest [4,49,54] and we have adapted these in light of recent findings. First, it is important to reconsider some of the previous work on specific membrane protein turnover in light of the general regulation of trafficking by tension. For
