example, factors that affect shape or motility can cause tension changes that can dramatically influence the rates of membrane exchange. A more integrated view of the relative contributions of all the pathways will be more complete once membrane area and tension maintenance are put back in the equation. However, in most cases experimental data are still lacking. More quantitative estimation of the relative contribution of each trafficking pathway for membrane area turnover will be of great utility, as has been addressed [41]. Another important aspect is whether different cell systems rely on the feedback mechanisms of tension and area to control shape and adjust downstream functions, particularly during mitosis [56]. A major limit on our understanding is imposed by technological boundaries. Pulling membrane tethers with optically trapped beads [9] is currently the only direct way to measure membrane tension, but this system has several limitations [1–3]. A probe that senses more directly changes in membrane tension would allow measurements in systems in which the cells are largely inaccessible, such as during development or collective cell migration. However, as previously mentioned, some of the best characterized tension-sensitive molecules, the bacterial mechanosensitive channels, generally operate at a much higher threshold than the tensions found in mammalian cells and so would not provide the necessary dynamic range (although mutagenesis might lead to more suitable candidate probes). Whatever the design, such a probe would be a quantum leap in allowing researchers to address the underlying influence of membrane tension across the biological spectrum. Although membrane tension provides a simple mechanical mechanism for linking diverse pathways of membrane trafficking and motility, there are many aspects of membrane tension that are not understood. For instance, the tension-related processes discussed in this review are dynamic in nature, but how their relative rates influence their dependence on and contribution to membrane tension is unclear. Indeed, membrane fusion, membrane deformation, and cytoskeletal remodeling can all occur in the subsecond to second range and understanding how they are interconnected remains a technical challenge. Future work can provide important insights into the mechanisms of signaling from tension to biochemical pathways linked to myosin contraction and exocytosis. Furthermore, the events in mitosis provide an extreme example of membrane tension effects on motility and membrane trafficking. With the development of new probes for tension, a more complete picture of the sequence of events should emerge.
